What will he do? ČSSD in Prague does not know Voldemort or a patisserie
The new city councillors from the ČSSD will apparently have to overcome a certain language barrier in order to understand their old-new colleagues from the ODS in the Prague council and in the assembly.
The daily "tested" Aktuálně.cz members of the new ČSSD council as they know the notorious slang that has arisen in the town hall during the last years when Prague was governed by the current coalition partners.
The coded vocabulary, which the Prague political elite introduced during the previous era of Mayor Pavel Bém, describes some of the most famous figures, situations and causes in the capital.
Surprisingly, it turned out that the new councillors did not understand the familiar terms very well.
At least that's what they claim.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"I really don't know."
"I am rather a novice in Prague politics," Lukáš Kaucký, the councilor for culture, responded to the test of the "godfather" dictionary.
And although he is a political veteran, Councillor Karel Březina reacted similarly.
For example, the term "golf hole".
"It's the only term you give me that I use from time to time."
"Otherwise, I don't accept slang in general."
From the glossary, whose expressions the daily Aktuálně.cz published in June this year before the ODS election congress, the editorial board selected six examples, mostly those that are notoriously associated with the Prague City Hall.
The socialists were supposed to explain the terms "Voldemort", "the biggest golf hole in Prague", "go to a pastry shop", "bull's neck", "betrayal of the capital" and "metal sheeting".
Three of the councillors agreed with the quiz, the fourth - Antonín Weinert, who is to head Prague's education system in the future - first promised an interview, but later did not answer the phone.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, refused the test outright.
"I don't deal with these things at all, and I won't evaluate how the Civic Democrats are talking."
"I'm now figuring out how we're going to understand each other within our programs," he said.
As has already been mentioned, Councillor Lukáš Kaucký would reportedly not recognize in the headline above that we are talking about an influential businessman and friend of former mayor of Bém, Roman Janoušek.
"Voldemort" means nothing to Kaucký, and the only term he correctly guessed in the exam is "the biggest golf hole in Prague".
"That's the Blanka tunnel," says Kaucký, and immediately adds: "But I know it more from the newspapers."
"I'll have to pay for a language course," he jokes.
The golf hole as the Blanka tunnel is deciphered not only by matador Karel Březina, but also by the councillor for the environment Lukáš Plachý.
Both Social Democrats know who Voldemort really is, and Lukáš Plachý is also familiar with where to find this character - he suspects the meaning of the expression "go to the pastry shop".
"I think that means going to some Prague company," Plachý is close to deciphering that it is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
Like Březina, he points out that he gained his knowledge from newspapers rather than using such a vocabulary.
In the Social Democrats, according to the test participants, there is no such well-established glossary of slang terms.
"I've consulted with my colleagues, but it looks like we don't really have anything like that."
"We call each other by names, sometimes abbreviations and distortions of names are used," says the chairman of Prague's ČSSD, Petr Hulínský, nicknamed Hulda by party members.
"At school they called me Birch, but I don't know if my colleagues call me that too," Karel Březina admits to his own nickname.
The newspaper has tried Aktuálně.cz name and it works.
Councillor Weinert is Děda or less friendly Dědek for party members, councillor Miroslav Poche, who drew attention to himself before the election by fraudulent in sponsoring the party, has the nickname "Igráček" among some of his colleagues.
Nicknames are also the only thing that the Social Democrats allow in internal party language.
Hulínský apparently does not like to hear Hulda, but the daily Aktuálně.cz noted another nickname of the Prague chairman.
The "Doctor of Baton Law" is said to recall that Petr Hulínský received his JUDr. degree at the Bratislava Police Academy.
Government wants to curb torture of 'witches', brochure published
Women declared witches in Burkina Faso have several features in common.
They belong more to the older generation, they cannot participate in work, for example, for health reasons, they are single and do not have children.
The one who "becomes" a witch is sent into isolation so as not to endanger the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer this fate."
"Even young, healthy women are not pushed back, because they help with work and give birth to children," says a nun who cares in a special house in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso for more than a hundred women who have been expelled from their ranks by their community.
The local government has now decided to crack down on the unusual "social measure".
It has published an information brochure to help curb witch-hunts.
But there is a catch.
"More than 70 percent of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," Die Standard said of the disadvantage of written education.
Accusations of witchcraft are common in other African countries as well.
In Ghana, which borders Burkina Faso, seventy-two-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week after being tortured, doused with kerosene and set on fire by three women and two men.
The case was reported by the BBC.
The perpetrators claim it was an unfortunate coincidence.
According to their version, the woman ignited the oil that is used for ritual anointing.
He said he caught fire after the group wanted to "cast out the evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people regardless of their level of education.
Der Standard quoted a forty-two-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "Devourers of human souls have always been a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to moderate the witch hunt, in Gambia the president himself took part in it as recently as last year.
"After the death of his aunt, President Jammi of Gambia launched a large-scale witch hunt for the witches who allegedly participated in her death and tried to kill the president himself with black magic."
"He enlisted the help of shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's bodyguards, forcibly led randomly selected men and women from Gambian villages to the president's farm in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in a statement.
On the farm, the imprisoned people had to drink a potion made from herbs with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two prisoners did not survive their stay on the farm.
After international pressure, nearly a thousand prisoners were eventually released.
Bakala's tenant: He heats in the stove, he signed a higher rent
An older, stocky man stepped out the door of RPG Byty "uhlobarona" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried a folder with new leases for three apartments: his own, his daughter and his son, who is serving a prison sentence.
For all three, deregulation has just raised rents.
Instead of 3500 a month, my son will pay CZK 4100 for a 2+1 apartment of the second category from next year.
"And there is no hot water and petrama (solid fuel stoves, Editor's note) has to be heated," the man points his finger at his son's new contract, which he has power to sign.
"But I signed it," he explains, half angry and half resigned.
The civic association BytyOKD.cz, which has described the new lease conditions as "incorrect and immoral," advises tenants not to sign new contracts and wait until December 7 to publish instructions on how to proceed against them.
But the man just waves his hand at it.
"One says this, the other says that," he frowns.
The Ostrava region is becoming a great laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, the vast majority of apartments that still have non-market rents in the Czech Republic are waiting.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG waiting room in Havířov is one of four in the Ostrava region and on Tuesday at nine in the morning it is already full.
Right next to the door stands a security guard from a security agency and a summoning machine next to her.
"Lease 2011", a special button on its touch screen is lit.
One tap and a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
You don't even have time to read "157" and your number is already beeping on the large display under the ceiling of the waiting room.
In half a second, it's your turn.
After a while, an elderly couple comes to ask about the rent, but the rush in the waiting room apparently does not concern the new rents at all.
Most people came to solve common problems as usual - requests for repairs, insurance claims and the like.
Letters with new lease agreements in the Ostrava region have been delivered to mailboxes by tenants of most of the total of 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio since mid-November.
In letters, RPG Byty proposes a rent increase of 15 to 38 percent.
A special counter for new leases was opened at the Client Centre on 18 November.
"It's been going on for over a week, so it's just getting started," the workers behind the counter reply after a moment's hesitation when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakala's former miners' flats are a local hot-tempered topic.
Before the election, the deputy speaker of the parliament and Ostrava native Lubomír Zaorálek of the Czech Social Democratic Party (ČSSD) took it up quite loudly, and even now the local newspapers are full of it.
"Twenty years after them, I want a new floor."
"Not even pos.. They didn't replace the plate in the toilet," the man mentioned in the introduction is relieved.
So far, according to the workers, pensioners are coming the most to see if they get a discount on rent if they sign on time, as RPG promises them in a special offer.
Other tenants who sign a new contract by December 15 will also receive a half discount on the February rent.
But the Havířov "deregulation" counter is certainly not overwhelmed with questions.
"Of yesterday's 360 clients, only about forty to fifty people were here because of the rent for 2011," the workers behind the counter estimate.
RPGs on the web and on their bulletin boards propose individual negotiation of contracts where necessary.
However, if the lease is not agreed by both parties, it will have to be determined by an independent court.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only possible and completely legitimate legal procedure," the RPG warns on its website.
"No one will be judged here," thinks one of the employees of RPG Byty, and the man on the street in front of the client center partially agrees with her.
"I have a pension of 13,000 and I have five thousand left for food, I don't have what it takes to sue," he said.
But the worker immediately becomes uncertain.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek tells them in the media not to sign, so people are probably waiting," he reflects.
Rent control ends in most of the Czech Republic with the New Year 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, their increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rent still does not even reach the amount necessary for simple maintenance of the housing stock," says Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, that the neglect of the housing stock criticized by the angry tenant is, according to the homeowners, the main reason for the rent increase.
While in the five years between 2005 and 2010, RPGs could invest four billion in rents, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it is expected to be 5.2 billion.
Meanwhile, a large screen hanging from the ceiling opposite the padded seats of the Havířov waiting room repeats several red-highlighted information.
"The rent increase of 15% or less in 2011 affects 31,200 apartments, more than 90% of RPG apartments."
"And it will always be the most by CZK 7.50 per square meter per month," he appears on the screen.
Only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio will see their rents rise by 38 percent.
"In these cases, it is an increase from the extremely low amount of CZK 19.66 per square meter," the RPG points out.
For 2600 apartments, the rent will remain the same next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not drive up rents by leaps and bounds, but will be spread over four to eight years.
In addition, it adds another commitment: all the money from the rent increase (see the chart) will be put back into apartments, mainly into heat savings - new windows and insulation.
Priority should be given to people who sign an agreement to increase rents.
The offices also include a kindergarten, the architects understood
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect it to hide a mini-kindergarten with everything that goes with it - with colourful walls, imaginative furniture, a stack of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be visited by children of Arch.Design employees.
The design and architectural company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important Brno buildings have emerged, has been counting on space for its company mini-kindergarten since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs nearly 90 people, mostly in the baby boom age, and she wanted women planners to get back to work quickly.
Together with the possibility of part-time work, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees as part of the social program.
Builders thus have the opportunity to combine a demanding job with child care.
The mini-kindergarten was invented by the employees of Arch.Design themselves and with the support of the management they managed to get a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company mini-kindergarten is financed from the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (subsidies in the amount of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and ensure qualified personnel and operation for two years.
After the financial subsidy is exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design the company is obliged to run the mini-kindergarten at its own expense for a period of 3 years.
The preparation of the project took one year and Economy Rating significantly assisted with the grant application.
Care is provided by qualified staff, children are cared for all day by a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, so children can attend kindergarten without age restrictions, yet most of them are older than 3 years.
Because it is a "mini-kindergarten", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but during the day there are even more.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of status in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is comparable to the framework programme of pre-primary education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality education - from basic learning to preparation for school desks, English is also taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check on their child at any time and there are no stressful situations with delayed picking up of children from kindergartens far from the parents' workplace.
Thus, parents use their working time more productively.
It is no wonder that a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship is formed here.
Arch.Design has thus joined the ranks of Czech companies that offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and have strengthened personnel marketing through this program.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors by Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouths.
Such is Casa Batlló in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house earned the nickname House of Bones from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all this is typical of Antoni Gaudi's Art Nouveau.
The façade of the house plays dreamy lines, delicate colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
On close observation, one can see the geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order.
At night, the entire façade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the gloss of colors is even more intensified.
Winding and twisting shapes appear equally in interiors.
Wood in waves copies window frames, railings, door trims, peepholes and moldings.
Located in the Eixample district on the busy Passeig de Grácia shopping street 43, Batlló was a 1877 conversion by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea for an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
The Casa Batlló apartment building was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
He was assisted by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his design board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the property owner and the use of mosaics on the façade were created.
A number of other artists and artists also worked on the façade.
Working together on the Casa Batlló designs started Jujol and Gaudí's successful collaboration.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá and the Park Güell, which houses other works by Gaudí.
Soon after its completion, the house earned the nickname "House of Bones" from the locals due to its organic shapes.
Others began to call it the "yawning house" because of the specific mechanism of opening the windows.
It is also said that on the top of the building is depicted the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a central heating system unique for his time with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five degree inclination.
When creating it, Gaudí absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not let them bind him.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data he provided about the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, during completion, the city council was horrified by the result and asked for a remedy.
The councillors were bothered, for example, by the fact that the construction interfered with the pillars and the public sidewalk.
It was never remedied, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the call of the city district, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two top floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social salon, and on the third floor bedrooms and private parts of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented by a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is intersected by a staircase, which can be climbed to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors, and a larger company can communicate comfortably with each other without retaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to a new façade, the house with Gaudí's reconstruction also received an unconventional roof and two extra floors.
Gaudí's play with light, blue and white glazed tiles lining the inner courtyard and skylights is also impressive.
The play of two colors gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark light, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun's rays.
Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and spectacular apartment open to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the one hundred and fiftieth anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed with the tours because they found it to be a very convenient business and they also expanded the tours to include common and attic areas, including a roof terrace.
The entrance fee to the monument is certainly not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes have a twenty percent discount.
The sum is well above the price of admission to Gaudí's other buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the true atmosphere of a house with dragon turrets, you must quickly make friends with one of the inhabitants of the apartment building and visit him right at home.
How to choose a mattress and base: women have different requirements than men
Not the flashy bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface, i.e. the mattress and base, give the basis of a really good bed.
However, they must complement each other harmoniously to suit a particular user.
When choosing, a lot of things decide, from weight, height, age, health status and sex of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and base are purchased.
Archetype?
For example, latex mattresses are not suitable for weekend cottages, where there is no regular heating, because they "heat up" more slowly.
In addition, they tend to have a significantly higher weight than a standard polyurethane mattress.
In doing so, it is necessary to turn them over regularly.
If they do not have a lot of venting ducts in the core, and they are still lying on a solid plate, they retain moisture: mold could also appear under them.
Habit is also decisive in the selection.
Who has spent a long time abroad, where very high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, will hardly feel comfortable on a low and hard surface.
"Almost all the hockey players who came back from the NHL complained to me that they didn't sleep here."
"For their battered shoulders, heels and hips, they needed mattresses with a softening layer of lazy foam."
"These are also recommended for people with diabetes who have a nervous system disorder, so they poorly take 'information' from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
Many hockey players, but also other customers, were looking for mattresses with lazy foam years ago.
"Today it's fine, suitable mattresses have for example Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico."
You don't have to be an NHL guy to appreciate lazy foam.
This "miracle" works simply.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape according to the heat absorbed, or adapts to your warm body.
Nothing pushes you, at night you will not roll over like after a difficult match.
You just sleep better.
Lazy foam also works as a protection against bedsores.
When choosing a mattress size, add the length of your foot to your height, which is about 21 to 34 cm.
Both a man and a woman with a height of about 180 cm need a bed of 210 to 220 cm.
The minimum width for one should be 90 cm for a double bed, i.e. a total of 180 cm.
For single beds, for example, singlelists, at least 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
For convenience and possible visit.
"Otherwise, the rule for bed width is simple: when lying on your back, you should keep your hands comfortably slightly bent at the elbow," advises Helena Prokopová, guildmaster of the Guild of Upholsterers and Decorators, who has been dealing with the issue of healthy sleeping and ergonomics of furniture for many years and lectures at vocational schools.
For a double bed, everyone needs their own base and mattress, but be careful when buying to match the heights of the mattresses.
Otherwise, you will have no choice but to mount the grates at different heights, but you may not be able to do this with each bed frame.
Foam mattresses should have a height of at least 14 cm, types with a spring frame at least 15, of which at least three centimeters count on the forming and baking layer.
"When touching your hands or touching the mattress, you definitely must not feel the springs," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of base.
Fully upholstered beds, where the mattress and subfloor are like fused Siamese twins, have no place in bedrooms.
Mattresses are poorly ventilated, their cover cannot be washed, which is already common today.
And because we normally sweat 0.2 to 0.75 l of sweat per night, it is clear that after five to seven years, the mattress will begin to resemble one large (and clogged) strainer.
That is why experts reject advertising slogans about mattresses lifespan of up to 25 years, or even lifetime warranty.
However, everything has its buts.
And therefore practical advice from sellers: for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, do not give up hygiene and washing removable cover, but rather add a mattress protector that you can easily remove and wash.
Although mattress covers with zippers around the entire circumference are commonly produced today, so that when unfastened we get two parts (very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), the handling of larger types (and with one person) could still resemble a fight between a light weight in the ring and a heavy one.
Do you have a solid board in your bed instead of a grate?
Never!
A maximum of a bed intended for one night's visits.
However, still provide the board (if it does not already have them) with ventilation holes and use a mattress with a spring frame and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (of it. Taschenfederkern) and baking layer.
Polyurethane mattress does not belong on such a base.
For non-positioning slatted bases with 14 to 18 lamellas, latex or sandwich mattresses (such as a combination of latex and coconut) will be suitable, but it is always worth slatting with a larger number of lamellas, 28 or more, where the slats in the loin area are doubled and their stiffness can be regulated.
Mattresses with a spring frame do not belong on positioning lamellar bases because they do not react to positioning.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the slats, you can also enjoy the so-called shoulder cradle.
It is a special attachment of the lamellae, which allows you to push or even tilt the lamella so that the sleeper's arm is nicely "sinked".
For men who have "shoulders over the whole back", definitely an important thing.
Even mattress manufacturers remember it, who in the "men's" began to use a softening zone just in the shoulder area.
They also remember women - they give them a softer surface in the hip spots.
For the most demanding customers there are aileron or plate grates with so-called multitorsional suspension.
The pressure spreads to multiple points and the voltage decreases.
But beware, as soon as you use the wrong pillow (large and "puffy") on the right mattress and base, most of the "plus" disappears.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the tips reach only to the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
As a suitable size, 50 x 60 cm is recommended, which is preferred, for example, in Scandinavia.
When lying on its side, the pillow should balance (along with the shoulder cradle of the base or the softened zone in the mattress) the height of the shoulder.
Modern mattresses have something in common with the original grass-filled straw mattresses.
Their manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least additives.
The trend is simply organic for mattresses.
Raw materials from crude oil, from which polyurethane foams are made, are being replaced by natural oils, for example, from castor and soy.
Soybeans are used by almost all well-known manufacturers.
"Bio mattresses mean that the core is made of a material of purely natural origin," explains Petr Vašíček from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the production of mattress covers, one of the first was aloe vera.
But you can also indulge in microcapsules to release the fresh scent of the forest or lavender.
There is also a division for men and women.
While men are "cooled" by birch plant extract so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, women, on the contrary, "heats" the covers for women.
Red pepper extract increases blood circulation, making it warmer to the weaker sex.
Today's favourites?
Mattress made of cold foam (it has larger pores with broken cellular structure, so it is more breathable than conventional polyurethane and offers better elasticity.
The combination of different stiffness of cold foam and "lazy" foam creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, loins and heels should be.
For a quality mattress you will pay from seven thousand crowns and above.
Those that meet health parameters, tend to have a lower VAT rate, are considered as medical aids.
Gumotex was the first in the Czech Republic to achieve this advantage.
Saving on a mattress and base is not easy.
Sometimes you can use the actions of manufacturers or retailers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers a Duofreeze mattress with Memory foam sewn into the cover for CZK 11,990.
However, the second one can be purchased for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with open cellular structure and high density was started at a "cosmic" pace by Temdur.
It was originally created as material for NASA because astronauts were subjected to enormous overload during launches.
Tempur softens in the heat, on the contrary, it hardens in the cold.
It adapts perfectly to the warm human body and distributes its pressure optimally.
It is therefore ideal against bedsores, but also for increasing sleep comfort.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses, but also for medical products, such as special pillows under the legs, which relieve the legs and venous system.
Domestic manufacturers use, for example, Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents want people tracking devices, so they want to watch their children
Fear for their own child leads more and more people to the idea of GPS babysitting.
A system originally created for searching for cars can also track the movement of people, thus helping in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is still about the size of a matchbox, but soon it may only be as big as a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Anička and began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying, but another means of reducing the likelihood of a tragedy happening," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment to the Czech market.
"I concede that in some cases such devices may be misused, for example when they are put in a bag by someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet come across such a case."
"Most of the time, customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know for what purpose the "box" serves and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not want to wear anything like this, he will simply get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in losing things on purpose when they don't want to be in control."
"Parents used to have great expectations of mobile phones, but they can be turned off just like these tracking devices," Bočková says.
According to her, it is also questionable whether such a device would actually help in the event of an attack.
"When it comes to a planned abduction, the perpetrator almost always makes sure that the child does not have any electronics with him that could reveal his location."
"It's a phone now."
"When tracking devices start to proliferate, they will look for them as well, because their sales will surely be supported by massive advertising."
"In this case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he admits that such a device can help in the event of a sudden paedophile attack.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even if the surveillance device is immediately destroyed after an attack, its presence can help.
"The device can be set to periodically send a location after a certain period of time."
"Should it be damaged, at least the last location of the person concerned will be available."
"More expensive devices also have built-in tiltmeters, so even if a person just slips and remains motionless, the device immediately sends a warning with a position," says Čech.
According to him, a similar service can be performed by smartphones with navigation, where you just need to upload special software.
The problem with current surveillance units is that they are either devices similar to pendants the size of a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
There is always a risk of their loss.
According to Pilin of Macro Weil, a device that looks like a regular digital watch is now being tested.
"This will have the biggest advantage that the potential aggressor may not recognize the tracking device at all."
"Or he only recognizes them after some time, and that can give the police extra time," he adds.
Whether tracking devices evolve into bracelets or pendants, they will still use the same technology used for guarding cars.
It is a combination of GPS positioning (used by conventional car navigation) and the function of a mobile phone that reports the current position of the car.
The army has incendiary cords that would encircle the Czech Republic. But it only lasts two years
The Czech Army bought 445 km of lines that detonate explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defence delivered 224 kilometres of lines to the warehouses.
The army thus has 225 years of reserves.
The problem is that the durability of the cords is two, maximum four years.
The army bought the detonating cords from STV Group, a. s. for CZK 40 million.
The General Staff, justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of detonating cords, wrote back to MF DNES that soldiers consume 60 kilometers of fuses a year during training.
However, the calculations of army pyrotechnics contacted by MF DNES show that then all generals, army command officers, secretaries or cleaners would have to undergo very intensive pyrotechnic training every year.
Defence Minister Alexander Vondra and Army Commander Vlastimil Pick included.
This is the only way to justify the annual consumption of an army of sixty kilometers of fuses.
This length corresponds to 25,000 explosions.
And even if that were the case, the army's reserves would last for more than a decade.
If, on the other hand, it were true that a maximum of two meters of detonating cord is enough for the basic training of each new professional, as experts say, then the army has secured with a fresh purchase - even with increased consumption of engineer or special forces - supplies for the aforementioned 225 years.
Soldiers of the Rapid Deployment Brigade recently complained personally to Minister Vondra that they have almost no ammunition for small arms, so even shooting is limited due to lack of money.
Not to mention the lack of underwear.
"It also bothers me that they buy such a large number of fuses from us repeatedly."
"But it's their decision and they certainly know what they're going to do."
"For us, the army is a good customer, which we as traders try to satisfy," says Jan Děcký, Sales Manager of STV Group.
Ministry of Defense spokesman Jan Pejšek also justifies the hundreds of kilometers of purchased cord by the fact that the army will have stocks of this "ammunition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký from STV Group speaks only of a four-year lifetime of a fuse, and police or army pyrotechnics even only two years.
"With perfect storage, it can be the four of them," says one of them, who as a soldier does not want to be named because of criticism of the military.
At the end of its service life, each ammunition must be carefully tested to ensure that it is still reliable and does not endanger the lives of soldiers.
However, these tests are not free and cost extra money.
Another argument of the ministry is a quantity discount on 445 kilometers of detonating cords.
"They cost us sixty percent less than last year's two-hundred-and-forty-four-kilometre delivery," says spokesman Pejšek, interpreting the position of the Ministry of Defence buyers.
Just for comparison: the annual consumption of firing lines of police pyrotechnicians who dispose of ammunition from the Second World War or the one left by the Soviet army has not exceeded 1,500 meters for several years.
And the police always order just enough to use up the ammunition before the end of its useful life.
It has proven itself for the safety of pyrotechnicians, and it can also obtain more modern and therefore more reliable types of cords more flexibly.
The Ministry of Defence already has considerable difficulties with the disposal of tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the two-hundred-thousand-strong Czechoslovak army was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians contacted by MF DNES, the Czech one will face the same problem in a few years: it will dispose of hundreds of kilometers of old fuses that it now buys "cheaply".
To this day, I draw on the contacts I have gained thanks to the competition
