Poll that removes nonsensical regulations
The Absurdity of the Year poll is part of the business competition for the fourth time.
Some nonsensical regulations have already been repealed.
The infamous winner of the next year of the Absurdity of the Year survey was the obligation to bring documents to the office that are also accessible to officials online.
It was decided by more than a third of the less than four thousand voters.
For example, the Social Security Administration required a paper extract from the Commercial Register, although an official can obtain it with two clicks of a mouse.
Thanks to the poll, that will change.
"The Czech Social Security Administration will no longer require an extract from the Commercial Register during inspections of insurance payers," ČSSA spokeswoman Jana Buraňová said.
Shining a light on all the regulations and regulations that companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must comply with and abolishing the nonsensical ones is the purpose of the Absurdity of the Year competition.
This year, for the fourth time, it is part of a business competition organized by Hospodářské noviny and is becoming increasingly popular among the public.
If last year about three thousand voters took part in the voting, this year there were almost four thousand.
And no wonder, there are still plenty of various legal obligations that serve only to delay business.
"For example, in the number of tax return papers, we are at the forefront of the world," says Karel Havlíček from the Association of Small and Medium-Sized Enterprises and Crafts of the Czech Republic.
In recent years, simplifying business has become a stated goal of all governments.
Compared to the rest of the world, however, the situation in the Czech Republic is not much improving.
According to the World Bank, the Czech Republic ranked 74th in terms of business conditions, which is eight places worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year competition was first announced in 2006 and runs annually according to the same scenario.
Anyone can submit administrative and bureaucratic nonsense every year from April to the end of September, when the competition deadline is closed.
To log in, use the web address www.firmaroku.cz Then the organizer of the competition selects seven candidates for the "anti-prize" and lets the public vote for it over the Internet on the www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz websites during October.
The absurdity that gets the most votes wins.
This year's survey was entered by more than a hundred, more precisely 105 regulations and regulations that are meaningless.
Tips were sent by entrepreneurs, but also by professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the competition were, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of motorways and expressways pay tolls, or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two toilets paint every two years.
The list of this year's seven designs is published on the competition website.
The announcement of the competition, which always takes place at the beginning of November on Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of the hapenning, which is regularly attended by personalities of political and social life.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of Small and Medium-Sized Enterprises and Crafts of the Czech Republic, and Petr Kužel, president of the Czech Chamber of Commerce, assisted at this culmination of the competition.
"Economic prosperity cannot work where the state puts obstacles in the way of entrepreneurs, so my goal is to abolish at least thirty paragraphs every year that only unnecessarily complicate business today," said Minister of Industry and Trade Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to repeal nonsensical regulations are not in vain.
In 2007, people were most bothered by the obligation of entrepreneurs to report three days in advance to the Trade Licensing Office in the place where the permanent establishment is located, the intention to go with the stand to an exhibition or pilgrimage.
This obligation was removed by an amendment to the Trade Licensing Act.
The second most voted obligation in 2007, which was to report to the Labour Office a business trip of up to 30 days on behalf of its foreign employee, was removed by the so-called green card law.
