Czech children get drunk with fernet and rum. Beer is out of fashion, it works slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka, exceptionally even a better brand of whiskey stolen from parents.
These are the drinks after which drunkards who are not even fifteen years old end up in the care of doctors.
An exception are not children who are treated from monkeys in the hospital repeatedly.
This is based on the experience of doctors who encounter similar cases in the receptions of children's wards of hospitals.
"Some beers or wines are completely unfashionable because it takes a long time to get drunk on them."
"The trend is definitely hard alcohol," Luděk Pelikán, head physician of the children's department of Hořovice Hospital in Central Bohemia, told Právo.
"If they manage to pull a bottle out of Dad's closet, it's whiskey, but otherwise fernet and vodka predominate."
"Vodka has the advantage that they pour it into the juice and it is not so much to smell of," explained the head physician.
Eva Jurinová, spokesperson for the Motol University Hospital, agrees with him.
"Most often it's fernet or rum."
"That's modern alcohol today, especially in elementary schools."
"In some cases, it was plum brandy that they had brought from home," Jurin said.
According to Dr. Pelikán, thirteen or fourteen-year-old drinkers are a relatively common phenomenon in hospital admission.
Before Hořovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for ten years at the paediatrics in Motol, where ambulances transport schoolchildren from far and wide.
"One girl has been lying with us about four times."
"She started her career at the age of twelve, when she was brought to us with 3.5 per mille of alcohol in the blood in combination with ecstasy," the doctor described a particularly serious case.
"She was at the exhibition grounds in Holešovice at some dance party."
"Interestingly, her mother didn't find it strange that she didn't know about her daughter for 48 hours," the head doctor wondered.
It is the lack of interest of parents or even their considerable tolerance to drinking their own offspring that is considered to be the main cause of the growing drinking of children.
However, according to experts, addiction in the true sense of the word cannot be spoken of in children.
"The term alcoholic means several years of chronic dependence on alcohol with all the phenomena that go with it, and this is not the case in children."
"Those who use alcohol repeatedly tend to have a bad family-social background," explained Dr. Pelikán.
According to Jurinová's spokeswoman, about forty drunk children were hospitalized at the pediatric clinic in Motol by mid-November.
However, only those with severe intoxication who had to stay in the hospital get into the statistics.
Child drunks who are taken away by their parents after outpatient treatment or brought home by the police are not counted.
Apart from cases when children just sit down after school and drink a bottle of liquor, there are three seasonal fluctuations that can be relied on: witches, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"They're either drinking the grief of a bad report card or, on the contrary, celebrating the start of the holidays."
"However, for witches, I have experienced seven child drunks at the reception at once," Pelikán said.
A drunk who spends the night detoxifying under the supervision of doctors is paradoxically at an advantage over one who suffers an unpleasant hangover at home the next day.
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and glucose deficiency are relieved by irrigation infusions with glucose and nutrients that the body lacks.
"They are actually better off because they have a good awakening after that beautiful evening experience and nothing hurts them."
"They are just confused about where they are," admitted Pelikán, adding that he sometimes spoils the pleasant mood of patients by at least listing the costs that their treatment has involvement.
Transport by ambulance and hospitalization in an acute bed will cost tens of thousands of crowns.
"Sometimes I used it as an educational tool, when I then calculated directly to the children on the business card how much their drunkenness cost and that they could also spend the whole summer on a temporary job to earn money for that one party," Pelikán added.
However, health insurance companies do not resort to regression proceedings in which they would recover the costs of treatment from parents in cases of child drunks, he said.
Two L-159s are in foreign hands in Spain for the first time
