A longer index finger than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than their ring finger are less likely to develop prostate cancer.
That's the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
It may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the University of Warwick's Institute for Cancer Research.
The finger could help determine which men should get tested for prostate cancer, especially when combined with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues followed more than 1500 prostate cancer patients in Britain and over three thousand healthy men in parallel.
More than half of the study participants had an index finger on their right hand shorter than their ring finger.
They were just as likely to have prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, for those who had an index finger longer than the ring finger, the risk dropped by 33 percent, and for men under sixty, the drop was 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - seems to reflect the different levels of sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone promotes growing prostate cancer.
Professor Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former president of the Czech Academy of Sciences, told the Czech News Agency that he has a cursory knowledge of the study, but that the relationship between finger length and cancer has not been "completely proven".
