Technology from the fifties is not suitable for anything else.
The CIA presented a video with out-of-focus satellite images.
Using computer animation, she clarified where the reactor components might have been before the destruction, a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear center.
In addition, photographs were submitted that showed the building up close or even from the inside.
The reactor was said to be shortly before start-up, but still without fuel elements.
Today, more than three years after the bombing, not much more is known than then, and the puzzles have even gotten bigger over time.
Former U.S. President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that the CIA was pretty sure before the attack that Syria was building a reactor at el-Kibar, but basically had no basis that there was an "active nuclear weapons program" in the country.
Some intelligence correspondents in Europe are even more cautious, referring only to an "alleged reactor," even though they consider the CIA's presentation "credible."
