Asked last summer how confident he was that he had a reactor in front of him, a senior UN diplomat said the IAEA had "enough material to ask questions".
The rubble of the supposedly "disused military building" was quickly cleared by the Syrians and the terrain was properly leveled.
Nevertheless, in June 2008, an IAEA team led by former Chief Inspector Olli Heinonen found traces of man-made uranium in el-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA has received, through a member state, satellite photographs of commercial vendors from the period immediately after the attack, which should be more accurate than those presented by the CIA.
Unfortunately, these shots are not on the market, because they were exclusively bought by an unknown customer - maybe Israel.
Therefore, the IAEA cannot confirm their authenticity.
Syria has always claimed that it never had a secret nuclear program and has not built a reactor.
The uranium comes from Israeli weapons, Damascus said.
