Since then, Damascus has refused to discuss the matter - as well as satellite images.
In addition, he forbade inspectors a second inspection of el-Kibar and access to the rubble of the bombed building.
But Israel, too, is stubbornly silent.
"We will never comment on this," Ehud Olmert, the ruling prime minister at the time, recently confirmed the official position.
The investigation into the case has dragged on fruitlessly since June 2008 and is "growing into a serious problem with regard to the credibility of the office," as a senior Western diplomat admitted at the IAEA's headquarters in Vienna - a serious violation of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons, which the IAEA oversees.
The IAEA sees three other facilities as key to moving forward with the alleged reactor — and unlike it, they still exist.
