The independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington (Isis) has identified these objects and found a complex of buildings in satellite images that is believed to be one of the suspicious objects.
It is apparently located inside or in the immediate vicinity of a military base - precisely for this reason Syria refuses IAEA access to these three sites.
In Vienna, it was said that the Syrians are afraid of a so-called fishing expedition - that the IAEA would be sent in advance by the US to track down military bases.
Nuclear detectives were alerted to the facility by the U.S. Secret Service.
The IAEA has evidence and satellite images that material was transported back and forth between these three sites and the square at Euphrates.
In Vienna, a senior Western diplomat said at least one facility should be "related to fuel production."
However, there is "no evidence of sensitive activities", i.e. uranium enrichment and reprocessing; processes that are required for the production of nuclear weapons.
The type of reactor is powered by uranium, which is not enriched.
But where the uranium comes from, and where it would later split off plutonium into a bomb, there are only probable estimates for these central questions.
It is also not known whether the debris, which could hide important clues, are hidden in these three locations.
As if hundreds of loads of trucks have disappeared from the face of the earth, no one seems to have any information where the rubble went.
Only a few kilometers from el-Kibar and on the other side of Euphrates lies the al-Tibni salt mine, which Syria had inspected in 1998 as a suitable warehouse for radioactive waste, is considered unlikely by the IAEA.
