Common Practice of Democracy
Support for democracy in Latin America is growing, as is support for private enterprise.
Crime is a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is considered more influential by many regions than the United States.
These are some of the results of the latest Latinobarómetro survey, which took place in 18 countries and was published exclusively in The Economist.
As the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can track changes in attitudes across the region.
This year's survey, which took place in September and early October, is dominated by two related things.
The first is that Latin America is in a rather cheerful mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several Pacific countries in South America (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen from a low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy was recovering after a deep decline in output last year.
But only about half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous areas, are staunch Democrats, dragging down the regional average (see Chart 2).
Some 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, the same number as last year, but a large increase compared to 25% in 2001 (Chart 3).
Some 34% said they trust the parliament in their country and 45% trust the government, again the same figures as last year, but a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, an economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
Support was created during the global financial crisis, probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social safety net has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again to 32% that year.)
However, the mood changes across a wide range from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is rarer in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crime worsened.
For only the second time since the surveys began, more respondents across Latin America see crime rather than unemployment as the most important problem (see Chart 5).
Roughly 31% say either they or their close relatives were victims of crime last year, but that's down from 38% last year and is also the lowest figure since 1995.
More robust economic performance is reflected in growing support for private entrepreneurship and the market economy: some 71% of respondents across the region say that private entrepreneurship is essential for development, up from 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that a market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of the same opinion (and 80% support private entrepreneurship there), although their leftist president, Hugo Chávez, expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is the leading country in the region, as mentioned by 19% of respondents (up from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, up from 11% last year)
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, with Venezuela enjoying success in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic, and Nicaragua.
