Tiptoe to the center
In the weeks she was suddenly widowed, Cristina Fernández, Argentina's president, has benefited from public sympathy, with her popularity rising from 20% to more than 50%, the highest level since she was elected in 2007.
Yet turning that success into a successful campaign for a second term in next year's elections may depend on a grieving Ms Fernández giving up the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And everything will be based on these signs.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued his economic policy after his wife successfully became president, had a habit of drawing up budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend additional income at will.
Mrs Fernández's government lost its majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition split and was further destabilized when Mr Kirchner died of a heart attack on 27 October.
Some members of the ruling Peronist political movement joined Ms Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (in which the government was slapped and accused of corruption), Congress failed to pass the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to argue," the president said.
The 2010 budget will now also apply to next year, with the president having more room to spend as she pleases.
The economy is overheating: growth of up to 9% is likely this year.
The official inflation rate now stands at 11.1%, but many private estimates and trade unionists speak of a figure that is close to 30%.
Mr Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was suffering from economic collapse, has prioritised growth and poverty reduction, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, burdened the private sector, and purged INDEC, the statistical agency that had agreed to monitor official inflation statistics.
Can President Fernández now moderate this policy?
She called for negotiations between private businesses and union leaders.
And its officials say they want to limit wage growth to 18% next year.
The economy was supported by the rise in world prices for exports of Argentine agricultural products.
But inflation was disrupted by growth based on the great devaluation of 2002.
That may be why President Fernández is making it clear that she wants to restore Argentina's financial ties with the rest of the world.
Earlier this year, the government struck up an agreement with bondholders who had previously refused to restructure a debt Argentina defaulted on in 2001.
Now President Fernández is facing an agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which she owes some $6.7 billion.
Kirchners always insisted on keeping this fact in sight of the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Amado Boudou, the economy minister, announced that the fund would provide "technical assistance" to design a new national consumer-price index that would resemble an introduction to INDEC cleanup.
It is not yet clear whether President Fernández will want to remain in politics after her term of office, when her husband is no longer by her side.
If he wants to stay, he needs to win the support of a middle class tired of Kirchnerism.
By the time Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy will wane.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether it will be necessary to quietly renounce many of her husband's views in politics.
Half a boost for China
Taiwan's voters are closer to the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother across the sea?
More than 7.5 million voters, 70% of those entitled, voted for mayors and city councils in five districts on November 27, which can be considered a broader assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
President Ma himself represents the feelings that prevail towards the mainland and have a strong foothold in business relations, including a semi-free trade agreement, the largest normalisation of relations with China since 1949.
President Ma passed the test, but only narrowly.
Although his Kuomintang (KMT) party ended up winning three of the five mayoral offices, it failed to win by a majority vote.
In addition, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which is in favor of greater Taiwan independence, won nearly 50% of the total vote against 45% of the KMT.
If it was a presidential election, President Ma would be in trouble.
Since he was elected two years ago, his party's share of the vote has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP was together with the KMT in city councils.
The election played out like most Taiwanese elections, which include noisy election trucks and mass rallies with flags with scantily clad girls.
It even included the obligatory mysterious assassination attempt.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan, honorary chairman of the KMT, was canvassing for KMT candidates on the eve of the election.
A man from the crowd shot young Mr. Lien cleanly across the face, wounding him and killing a spectator.
Bizarrely, it was not determined whether the gunman intended to injure Mr. Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
In any case, Tsai Ing-wen, the head of the DPP, claims that the shooting affected the election, suspicion falls on the DPP and leads voters towards the KMT.
Perhaps the only big winner of the campaign was China.
It was remarkable how the question of the mainland itself remained in the background.
Instead, candidates struggled over plans for state housing and job creation.
Taiwan usually enjoys its de facto independence and hates China's military threats.
Thus, the KMT tends to avoid ties to the government in Beijing.
But this time, the DPP has also refrained from stirring up anti-Chinese sentiments.
It is a reaction to the fact and realization that Chinese trade is crucial to Taiwan's economic survival.
President Ma, for his part, confirmed that China's policy is acceptable to most of Taiwan.
The government in Beijing can be expected to continue commercial bribes, along with its strategy to lure Taiwan back into the fold.
China wasted no time in sending a negotiator to Taipei to arrange a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
Surely they would also like to see political integration, but in order.
It will be better to wait for this after the 2012 presidential election.
In any case, the DPP has discovered itself.
Two years ago, it was at a bad level: its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was sent to prison on corruption charges.
President in 2000-08 was a firebrand and supporter of clear independence.
But under the leadership of Ms. Tsai, a new generation has developed that is moderate, and the DPP is working hard to attract professionals and young people.
Ms. Tsai has been touted as the DPP's presidential candidate, such as Su Tseng-chang, who held office under Mr. Chen.
Their party is now doing everything it can to show that they too can cooperate with Beijing.
Ms. Tsai has published plans for research institutes to serve as a point of contact between the DPP and China, provided that their negotiations can take place without prior conditions.
Ms. Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party represents a "credible alternative" to Mr. Ma's hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems annoyed by this shift.
In a statement issued from his cell, he expressed the view that DPP candidates would be better off if they insisted that Taiwan was a separate country.
He even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatist, not to run for president.
But even without Mr. Chen's intervention, the DPP will struggle to choose among potential candidates.
The KMT is authorized to search for its own people.
Mr Ma's ratings were poor, despite the rapid pace of economic growth; KMT candidates did not want to campaign with him.
Its unpopularity seems to be based mainly on unemployment and the widening gap between rich and poor.
A KMT spokesman says it will reorganize its cabinet, as well as local branches.
Strongly promoted proposals to support Taiwan for rapprochement are curtailed.
At the same time, most Taiwanese citizens consider economic integration with China inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent publicist, "the point of no return has passed."
Grammy Nomination: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is a surprise in the category of Best New Artist
Speeches at the request of the president and the people are bound to notice.
Esperanza Spalding, the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer chosen by President Obama to perform at the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize ceremony, is billed as one of the surprises of this year's Grammy Awards with a nomination for Best New Artist.
Given that Spalding has been a celebrated figure on the jazz scene since 2008, when her album "Esperanza" was released, the nomination came a little late, but it's in line with Grammy rules, where an artist may not release more than three albums before "the public identity of the artist is established."
Her ambitious 2010 album Chamber Music Society certainly marked a step forward, and with her lighthearted vocal style and nimble hands with elements of pop, funk and Latin influences, we can talk about Spalding as a success scored by Norah Jones in 2003, the closest equivalent for Grammy voters looking for a similar jazz work in this category in recent years.
Elsewhere, the Grammy judges rightly praise the Vijay Iyer Trio's "Historicity" album in the instrumental album category, an exciting, refreshing ride for an album that was a hot favorite last year.
Iyer will compete against veteran saxophonist James Moody's Moody 4B and John Beasley's Positootly.
Trombone Shorty, a hoarse favorite from New Orleans and a frequent guest on HBO's "Treme," was honored in the contemporary jazz category, which is otherwise inclined to the albums of Stanley Clark, John McLaughlin and Jeff Lorber.
The wild Darcy James Argue's Secret Society with knowledge of steampunk won several well-deserved recognitions in the large ensemble category, with the competition of chamber jazz Childs Ensemble and the still courageous Dave Holland, whose live album with the octet "Pathways" created a beautiful example of how a bassist can have a free hand as a bandleader.
Grammy Awards nominations: Michael Daugherty, Steve Mackey lead in classical music category
Classical music nominations at the 53rd Annual Grammy Awards bring a wide range of musicians and composers from around the world.
The leading nomination goes to Michael Daugherty and his "Deus Ex Machina" for piano and orchestra, with five points, and Steve Mackey with his album "Dreamhouse", an eclectic orchestral work, with three points.
Among the nominees with ties to Southern California was Estonian composer Arvo Pärt's Symphony No. 4 "Los Angeles," a work commissioned through the Los Angeles Philharmonic and debuted at Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
The L.A.-based composer Avner Dorman and his Mandolin Concerto also have a chance to win the award.
Nominations in classical music are divided into 13 categories, which include orchestral, opera, choral and solo recordings.
The Classical Music Producer of the Year category has five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin and James Mallinson.
Nominations for classical albums went to Bruckner and his Symphonies Nos. 3 and 4 by the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty's "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" by the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey and his "Dreamhouse" from the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" featuring various artists; and Verdi's "Requiem" by the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and Chorus.
In the opera category, the nominees are Berg and "Lulu" by the Orchestra of the Royal Opera House; Adolf Hasse and "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" by Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho and "L'Amour de Loin" by the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin and "The Enchanted Wanderer" by the Orchestra and Chorus of the Mariinsky Theatre; and Arthur Sullivan and "Ivanhoe" by the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
Grammy-nominated composers for contemporary works include Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina," Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionatamente Plus," Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer."
Pärt's Symphony No. 4 premiered at Disney Hall in January 2009 for a performance recorded by the L.A. Philharmonic under the baton of Esa-Pekka Salonen.
The approximately 30-minute episode is called "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to former oil tycoon Mikhail Khodorkovsky, who is imprisoned in Russia.
Dorman and "Mandolin Concerto" was nominated for instrumental performances by a soloist with orchestra.
The L.A.-based composer said he wrote a 15-minute piece specifically for mandolin performer Avi Avital, who performed in concert with the Metropolis Ensemble based in New York.
"I wrote it using Middle Eastern tones and many North African rhythms," Dorman said in a telephone interview.
Conductor Pierre Boulez, 85, received a nomination in the category for orchestral performance, for leading the Chicago Symphony for recording Stravinsky's works.
Instrumental soloists who have received nominations include pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and harpist Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
Among the nominated vocal soloists, only women were represented this year, namely Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the transition classical category, soprano Jessye Norman received a nomination for her recording "Roots - My Life, My Song."
Planned mosque in Temecula receives approval by planning commission
The planned mosque in Temecula received the unanimous support of the local planning commission after more than five hours of often passionate public testimony.
Critics attacked the project for promoting terrorism and leading to the suspension of trade.
However, jurors decided Wednesday night that the new religious center was in line with local laws and would be aesthetically pleasing.
"A lot of good people have come to support this project — Christians, Jews, you name it," Hadi Nael, president of the Temecula Valley Islamic Center, said Thursday morning.
"As an American citizen, I'm very proud of that."
"It means that justice will always prevail."
"The opposition is minimal," he added.
"Those who are against it are just shouting loudly."
"We have really great people in our valley."
The meeting began at six o'clock in the evening and lasted until almost midnight, when most of the time was taken up by discussions with people who were for or against the center. Those voices were evenly divided, reports Press-Enterprise.
The discussion continued on the newspaper's website.
"There is no more America," one comment appeared.
"We are the Planet of the Apes with the Statue of Liberty sunk into the sand."
"America has fallen."
The planned Islamic centers have also sparked protests in other parts of the country, including near Ground Zero, the site of the Sept. 11, 2001, tragedy that took place when terrorists attacked New York City.
In Temecula Valley, Imam Mahmoud Harmoush condemned the violence.
His religious community of about 135 families had been plaguing Riverside County for years without incident, but he wanted more and more suitable space than the warehouse space he rented with a filter system manufacturer.
The new 24,943-square-foot mosque in Mediterranean-style architecture will also have two minarets and will rise to a height of 43 feet.
It would occupy a 4.32-acre site on Nicolas Road, approximately three miles east of Chaparral High School.
Opponents can still appeal to the city council about the project.
Arsenic-resistant microbes increase the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the scope for the search for new life forms on Earth and possibly beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth, and they say it's a sign that life has options that stand outside the main elements that have been thought to be fundamental until now.
"This organism has a dual ability."
"It can grow either because of phosphorus or arsenic."
"This fact is very strange, but it is not evidence that this is some form of truly 'extraterrestrial' life," said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of a report that appeared Thursday in the online issue of the journal Science.
For a long time, six main elements were considered essential for life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, scientists have found that the bacteria, discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue growing after arsenic is replaced with phosphorus.
"It starts to amaze you what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
The finding is significant for the search for life beyond Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report of the news released for discussion, which did not divulge details of the find, sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report revealed the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that power biochemistry, and that the set of elements we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element with another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It was not an accidental find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Institute of Astrobiology, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she reasoned that a microbe exposed to both elements might be able to replace one with the other.
"Arsenic is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"As a result, organisms can have a very hard time separating these elements."
"However, arsenic is so different that, like phosphorus, it doesn't work. When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which the bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better under the action of phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic substitution, it increases the possibility that a life form that uses arsenic may appear naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea of arsenic being replaced by phosphorus is not new, but there has never been an example to prove it.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and scientists speculated that earlier life forms may have used it.
"This suggests that there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it formed in the early Earth period," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy, and the National Institutes of Health
The remaining stolen dogs were found in Compton
The remaining two of the four show dogs stolen from the Bellflower Motel have been found. The Los Angeles County Sheriff reported Thursday.
Four show dogs — two Akitas and a Welsh pembroke corgis — disappeared on Tuesday when someone stole a 2006 Chevrolet Express van in which they were spending the night at the Bellflower 6 motel, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were discovered Wednesday afternoon and the other two dogs late Wednesday night, said Steve Whitmore, spokesman for the Los Angeles Police Department.
"The good news is that the dogs are fine," Whitmore said.
"They're in good condition."
"They were handed over to their rightful owners."
Whitmore declined to say exactly where the dogs were found, in what location, nor did he share details regarding their finding.
"The investigation is still ongoing."
"We don't want to talk about it," Whitmore said.
"We follow the rules."
The owners of the dogs, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, could not be reached to comment on the case.
They were overjoyed when their two Akitas were found at a shelter in Downey on Wednesday afternoon.
Sheriff's deputies found the van and two dogs separately in Compton.
Akita Trace, a three-year-old male named Trace and a 10-month-old, Didi, were uninjured, authorities said.
But Bunny and Peter, Welsh Corgi Pembroke Rickard and Peek breeds who had planned to compete this week in regional competitions on behalf of their Japanese owners, remained unfound until their discovery late Wednesday.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, are in town this weekend to participate in the AKC/Eukanuba National Championship in Long Beach, where they planned to show Trace.
The other dogs were scheduled to compete in other competitions scheduled in the days leading up to the AKC/Eukanuba show, Peek told The Times on Wednesday.
Southern California is just one stop on the couple's nearly month-long dog show travel.
On Monday night, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They often sleep in motels and park their car in front of their room window.
They also took three dogs with them - a boxer puppy, a Parson Russell terrier and a Brittany pointer - who stayed with them in a motel room.
Akitas and Pembroke Welsh corgis were left in the car, where it should have been cooler.
They opened the windows a little so that the dogs had enough fresh air in the car.
Peek and Rickard reported the car theft at 6 a.m. Tuesday.
Peek said he would offer a reward to anyone who took them to the missing dogs. Dogs are implanted with microchips to identify them.
It was unclear Thursday whether the prizes would be awarded.
Leo is ready to roar again now that MGM's restructuring is getting final court approval
After 18 months of turmoil and uncertainty, MGM has finally been given the green light to start over.
New York's federal bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially blessed creditors' "pre-packaged" plan to settle about $5 billion in debt, clearing the way for an 86-year-old entertainment company that focuses on producing and producing movies and TV shows.
Thursday's ruling that the plan meets U.S. bankruptcy code requirements leaves no legal obstacles for MGM to restart Spyglass Entertainment founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the heads of the slimmed-down studio.
The number of employees will drop to about 320 from the original more than 400.
MGM will not suddenly emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase agrees on planned financial resources to allow for a $500 million loan to fund MGM's new operations and production.
Now it's about merging with an investment bank that needs $75 million on its own, and funding is expected around mid-December.
The studio's restructuring process began in May 2009 when investment bank Moelis & Co. was hired to advise management on how to sort out its finances as management struggled to afford $300 million in interest payments annually.
That August, Chairman Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO of Enron and turnaround expert known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve the financial problems of MGM and the studio's 140 creditors took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties agreed to put the company up for sale at the end of 2009.
Although the auction attracted several bidders, none of them were willing to pay the $2 billion plus the funds demanded by creditors.
In the spring of this year, everything was back on the drawing board and the MGM team began working on a restructuring plan. After months of discussions and internal disagreements, the plan was finally approved by creditors in late October.
When MGM officially emerges from bankruptcy in the coming weeks, Moelise and Cooper's companies will receive multimillion-dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will be paid $9.5 million.
Cooper's firms, which collect $375,000 a month for their services that run the company, will receive a $4 million success fee.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM, which released only one film this year, and put together a proposal for seven or eight films to be released in early 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on the book "The Hobbit," along with Warner Bros. Bros.
The studio needs to arrange a special loan of between $265 million and $275 million to finance its share of the two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18% of MGM's debt, was looking for a merger with Lions Gate Entertainment, where he is the largest shareholder.
However, recent negotiations between the two companies have not resulted in an agreement.
