Introducing finer policing in China
As a city military instructor, Tang Shenbin walked around the square, strictly controlling his orders and issuing orders semi-loudly with military authority.
He wanted the female members—China's burly enforcers of urban order, feared and despised for their crackdown and penchant for violence—to convey an impression on the crowd of bystanders.
"Stand up straight!"
"Hurry up!"
Show them, he whispers softly, "what pretty girls look like!"
Four very young girls in white gloves and the same olive coats and trousers stood at attention.
Four pairs of black shoes are lined up as if by a ruler.
Four headgear fits perfectly on the hair, which is perfectly tied with blue and white ribbons.
"Personally, I think they look average," Mr. Tang said dismissively.
"The models are nice."
More than one government has tried to revive the image of city overseers in China.
One city mandated that new conscripts have a college education.
Guangdong province has changed its gray-green uniforms to supposedly more attractive blues.
Wuhan replaced staring with powerful weaponry in central China: in 2009, one report reported that 50 officers surrounded a snack cart and stared at the owner until the door-to-door salesman packed up and drove off after half an hour.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 people in Chengdu, chose surgery as their main image.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its municipal police force, who were selected specifically for their appearance, symmetry and young age.
The aim is to show, in addition to the rough side of the police, the gentler, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson herself would have trouble getting into secret Chinese urban groups.
Critics would argue for good reason.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce city ordinances, impose fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, police inspectors in Hubei province beat a bystander to death after he used his mobile phone to film their actions in a protest against a landfill.
Last year, police officers were trained in Beijing, and the training manual was stolen and posted on the Internet. The manual included, among other things, a description of how to effectively beat up offenders without signs of blood.
This year, a watermelon peddler in Shanghai got into a fight with five police officers and suffered injuries to the left side of the brain.
One video game full of violence, which can be downloaded online, shows Chinese police officers attacking street vendors.
"Chengguan scares the government," China Daily, the national edition, lamented last year after further discussion over tactics.
The paper read, "really thoroughly cleaned."
Skeptics say that such an approach is not enough.
After the county advertised interest in eight new female police officers in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News addressed the question of whether women have real duties or are just a distraction.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district required female applicants between the ages of 18 and 22 with a good figure and "five facial features in the right proportions."
Adepts should have a height higher than the average - that is, more than 1.6 meters.
Retired at the age of 26 is mandatory.
Officials say the work is too mentally demanding for women over 25.
"Their image is an important thing," one unnamed police officer said on Rednet.com government-like website.
"Female candidates must first demonstrate external qualities, which are then determined by others, such as height, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes the character and the "inner qualities".
Women are like flower vases, he said, adding, "In addition to being vases, they will also have other responsibilities."
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district city government, disagrees with this description.
But he noted that height requirements are also common in China for other jobs, for both genders.
As well as the requirement for symmetrical facial features.
Which means that the question of good looks is a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Disabled or crippled will certainly not apply.
"He cannot allow a lame or hunchbacked man to serve with us," Mr. Zheng said.
"His image wouldn't be good."
Liu Yi, who keeps watch in Baoguang Square near the monastery, is 22 years old, cheeks like apples and a finely shaped mouth.
She doesn't think the emphasis on her appearance is sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asked with a wry look.
Her dimply co-worker, 21-year-old Xu Yang, says, "Our job is to represent the image of the city."
They have no objection to their limited performance, they said, because their career ambitions are bigger than just herding businessmen into the aisles where they can do their business.
Every morning, the group faces more than a dozen marketeers who run around on foot or on bicycles, trying to sell as many dumplings and bowls of tofu as possible before being chased away.
"Mr. Wang, you must leave."
"We've told you this many times!" said Miss Xu as the marketeer began to run away, leaving his bike with the noodle cart for a time.
Police officers describe their duties as more monotonous than strenuous.
"It's basically the same thing every day," said Huang Jing, 20, who is studying marketing in her spare time.
"Great routine."
