Can politeness bridge the chasm?
After a campaign notable for its offensiveness and negativism, a small amount of courtesy emerged in Washington this week.
Is this the first sign of genuine bipartisan cooperation or just an illusive moment before a quick return to the party struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and House leaders yielded no major discoveries on the fundamental issues that must be discussed during the session.
In any case, it was a polite discussion dealing with the differences of opinion between the two parties, as well as defining their common responsibilities, rather than another empty episode of party struggle.
Wednesday's public session of the president's deficit committee was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain among members.
It seems clear that the close cooperation over a period of several months has built a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still divides members.
And it is quite difficult to argue that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both parties are now in a trial period, probing each other for signs of collegiality and compromise, while trying to assess the boundaries of public opinion and voter patience in the face of a renewed party war.
That is why Tuesday's meeting, and its later evaluation by the participants, was carried out with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too vast and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the situation that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it's a tax, spending, health care, or rights issue, both sides are miles apart.
However, the November elections were prepared by Washington at least quickly.
"It's not a question of whether regulatory issues have changed," said Pete Wehner, Bush's administrator, now at the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"These are inevitable after the elections.
The elections stirred up the emotions of the party members, and they then fell silent.
It's good."
On several issues, especially those to be discussed in the session, Republicans and Democrats have little chance of finding a solution.
Bush's tax cut expired at the end of the year, and no one considers it favorable.
Both sides want to find a way to protect some or all, permanently or temporarily.
Like a likely compromise on unemployment benefits only because Republicans can't watch them support tax cuts for the have-nots while denying unemployment benefits to the unemployed.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is already more optimism about a possible agreement on these issues, along with the ratification of a new opening treaty.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on fundamental issues will not necessarily lead to a bipartisan relationship when the 112th Congress convenes in January.
Rather, a period of disagreement is likely, or even inevitable, he said.
"After the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term returns to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism — which is largely widespread — that courtesy will lead them to genuine cooperation.
"I look at everything that happens between now and 2012 as a shadow box, with the main events occurring in 2012," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the formation of a new Republican majority in the White House and the tea party voters who helped create it.
Republican leaders now face the danger of hyperbole, knowing that they must live up to their promises and cut government spending and repeal the new health care law.
These adherents are clear in the initial responses to the deficit recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on the task of one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, in their opinion, to push the deficit issue to the public agenda in ways that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to present their plan as an official recommendation, and they have fought to get as close to that number as possible.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials on the jury, who suggest that on financial issues we have, at least today, a small foundation or will for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House and House Republicans.
The first will begin next year in the form of partisan conflicts, with Republicans calling on Obama to address the budget, taxes, and health care, followed by a period of greater partisan cooperation.
What causes the shift?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite partisanship in the last election, a majority of Americans want to continue to see two parties working together.
If it could lead to a stalemate, as it was in 1995, then both sides will watch public reactions very closely.
Anyone threatened with a reduction in votes is likely to change course and seek a compromise.
This may be an optimistic point of view.
Partisanship and direction are greater today than they were in the mid-nineties, and it turns out that a larger ideological divide has formed between Obama and the Republicans than it did with the Republicans and Bill Clinton.
At the same time, activists on both sides see 2010 as a prelude to a more important election in 2012.
Based on this reality, the courtesy that emerged this week would be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take a lot of effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
