The software suggests improvements in vehicles in real time.
Ever since Red Bull burst into the Formula 1 series in 2004, its history in this extraordinary world of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
Initially, no one took the possibilities of this newcomer team too seriously, and despite the recent upward trend, everyone was betting on Fernando Alonso's Ferrari triumph.
Without wishing to diminish the driving skills of champion German Sebastian Vettel or the capabilities of the Renault engine that powers his car, a legend has been born in the world of Formula 1 – the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has placed in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
In fact, it is a powerful software simulating marches, which the German company launched in 2007 for purposes far removed from motor sport.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software device, was used to design assembly lines in manufacturing plants around the world, in power plants and for high-precision instruments.
Its aim is to faithfully reproduce the product or simulate the process before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary mistakes and expenses.
PLM facilitated the development of Canon's camera, Sukhoi aircraft and Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, Head of Industrial Division at Siemens, explains that the use of the software enabled the Red Bull team to make modifications and improvements "in a few hours, in near real time" that are otherwise detected during races and trials.
Russwurm says that in 1992, the stables employed an average of 10 technicians who were able to make a maximum of three or four improvements in one period.
The Red Bull team now employs 180 young, highly qualified professionals equipped with powerful information technology, who analyse and design every type of modification of racing cars.
The Siemens executive explained that the PLM software is able to analyse and improve all elements of Red Bull racing cars except the engine, for which Renault is fully responsible.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety features are modified.
Changes can be translated from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced manufacturing systems using a laser and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit to this technical achievement is $40 million, which is the maximum that any Formula 1 team can spend in any period to improve its competitiveness.
Red Bull has set up a high-tech plant about 50 km from London to design and manufacture its race cars.
