Zapatero and the Red German Line
Berlin decided to keep the euro, but set conditions for the entire Union.
Market tensions provoked a twofold government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Zapatero proposed new adaptation measures, ranging from tax cuts for small and medium-sized enterprises, to the regulation of private intermediary agencies or the abolition of 426 euros for the unemployed without benefits, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the administrator of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30% of the state lottery.
On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former Prime Minister Felipe González, joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility for unleashing the current crisis.
How to interpret these emotions?
Let it be said in advance that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with the idea of keeping old traditions that many of the other members hold.
In the face of European resistance, speculation in Germany is beginning about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also, for example, Austria or the Netherlands, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to the mark - although now it may seem like science fiction, this version has wide public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to the German proposals, is to recast the euro with greater macroeconomic surveillance, budgetary stringency, fines for offending states, possible postponements of payments for some of them, and an extension of the possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is no room for prevarication now.
First, when both the International Monetary Fund and the European Commission fueled deficits in 2009, the German government pulled constitutional reform up its sleeve to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a discrepancy between what Germany thought was right (plans for austerity and stability of public finances) and what was practiced by its European partners, including France.
The second was shown by the Central European country when Merkel painfully delayed the decision to save Greece.
It was already the subject of harsh criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion that was also made public were strongly opposed to the Greek bailout.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again appeared with a clear position, calling for the European Union's conventions to be reformed so as to allow a member state to be rescued and, at the same time, to oblige private creditors to bear part of the costs.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it hastened the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, albeit in a somewhat watered-down form, was approved, and we should monitor the Union's reform process over the coming months, which should allow for these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells us all that, although measures need to be taken now that they seem to disagree with very much, from that date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mark the birth of a new currency zone in which offending states will be severely penalised and may be forced to announce postponements of payments, and the private sector will also have to bear part of the costs.
Germany is telling us that we must follow a strict path of growth with increased savings and investment rates, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital reserves.
Another option based on claims and building, with huge balance-of-payments gaps such as prevailed during Spain's boom years, is simply not tolerable.
