Sport and circumvention
Tricks such as those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show wit, not an intention to escape punishment.
The alleged contrived sending off of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on November 23 caused a sea of ink to be written about whether or not this was unsportsmanlike conduct and whether UEFA should eventually punish the two footballers.
As is known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team had clearly won), the named players one by one deliberately lost time at the moment when a foul should have been played, in order to provoke the referee, who showed them a second yellow card.
In this way, both players will fulfil their prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid finishing in the top of their group - and will be able, stripped of their cards, to continue to the next stage.
In the end, UEFA's disciplinary committee imposed a two-match penalty on coach Jose Mourinho and the offending players were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, rules that are unwritten but monitored.
Part of the discussion in this case arose thanks to the fact that Real Madrid (who boast of generosity and honour in their anthem, and who have already fined their players for similar acts) and the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adds another episode to his long history as a comedian and provocateur.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is to say, whether these acts involve circumvention of the law; These are, indeed, events that respect sporting rules, the meaning of which, however, seems to be trying to circumvent.
It is being discussed what type of damage such actions cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the requirements of sportsmanship is the physical inviolability of opponents, which in these cases was not violated, i.e. there was no violent play.
Another of these elements characterizing a clean game is to avoid players having an advantage over the opposing team due to their offense - which also did not happen here.
Thus, the paradox of the Real Madrid players' actions is the fact that there was no what we normally characterize as a ruse or circumvention of the law, there was no hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid a sanction, but this behavior should have been as obvious as possible in order to receive a penalty.
They waited and gladly received the punishment.
Another question, however, is what advantage the culprits will have from their intentional transgression.
Here it is necessary to state that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that no benefit will be achieved in the current match, because the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And even this is not a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously lies in the fact that players will start the next stage of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardise their participation in a future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, so at first glance the team can be eliminated, and besides, by doing so, the players will be punished and move to the second round of cards, in which one less card is needed to eliminate than in the first round.
So as the rounds go ahead, it won't be entirely clear if this is an advantage.
In short, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit, which involves making strategic decisions that allow maximum benefit to be obtained within the rules.
In the case we are dealing with here, the players did not aim to avoid punishment (which would be a clear case of circumvention of the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or running away from it.
Although the line between wit and circumvention of the rules is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly wit.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because there were two self-exclusions, and because of the way in which the transmission of instructions to provoke them from the management took place.
The damage to sporting principles by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
Battle of offers to host Christmas parties in Barcelona
This year's calendar dictates concentrate an avalanche of bookings on December 16 and 17.
The number of celebrations paid for by employees who want to spend between 20 and 30 euros is rapidly increasing.
Like Turkish honey or the lottery, with the arrival of December pre-Christmas parties are coming again, which still act as an oxygen bomb for restaurants and leisure facilities in Barcelona, but due to the crisis they have resulted in a struggle to win clients by lowering prices: almost everyone wants to spend 20 to 30 euros on food, according to the entrepreneurs and associations from the sector.
