The country's representative at the UN climate change conference COP16 assured that his country has made extraordinary efforts to reduce its carbon footprint, and said it stands by its promise to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45% by 2020.
China will keep its promise to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45% by 2020, Su Wei, the country's representative at the UN climate change conference, assured.
In his first public address at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, Su Wei assured that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and transform its industry.
He said his country has already invested $245 million over the past four years in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its goals and will continue to work on this matter together with the international community.
He reported that China's climate change strategy is divided into four items: dialogue, capacity building, institution building, and support for pilot programs.
They have already seen progress on all these points, including last year's passage of a new energy law that includes proposed targets to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, he explained.
He further stressed that in China, federal agencies worked in coordination with provincial and local authorities to achieve their goals in terms of energy saving, efficient energy use and reducing emissions.
Further, he said, various multi-year plans are in progress or have already been completed, funded by both the Chinese government and other governments.
For example, he said, the Energy Efficiency Programme, which has been put in place over the last five years and has received investment from the UN, the government and private initiatives.
A provincial climate change project, a project to replace fluorescent lamps with energy-saving light bulbs, and a mitigation and adaptation project are also underway, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country's expert adviser on climate change, assured that China's efforts have been greater than is generally thought.
For example, he described, greenhouse gas emissions per capita are 6 tons in China, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for a 9% historical share of emissions.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in terms of energy use – for example, it has increased energy efficiency by 20% over the past five years and expects to make further progress by 2020, he added.
