United States changes visa rules
People will need to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centres before the interview at the Consular Section; Costs will be lower and waiting times will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa process at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centres (ASC for short) before the interview at the Consular Department.
ASC staff will take the applicant's biometric information and this will be evaluated by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including:
The total cost of obtaining a visa will be lower, there will no longer be a fee to arrange an appointment, the second for processing the application and another for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for application visas (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for a business and investor visa.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to undergo an interview with a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC to present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Since biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who will require a second appointment with an interview at the Consular Section will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra $26 service fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
