World plan to restore lighting
Yesterday in Cancún, the UN proposed a plan to restore home, retail and industrial lighting in 100 countries with the aim of achieving a reduction in the greenhouse effect (GES) equivalent to almost one-third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the planet's climate between now and 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of large, concrete projects that the UN wants to push through in Cancún to compensate for the lack of hard-to-implement reduction commitments on the part of industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize 50 to 70% of the market, with fluocompact bulbs or, better yet, incandescent bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a substantial amount of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet due to lighting would be eliminated.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It's the equivalent of 70% of car fleet emissions across the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, major countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, among them Canada, engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GES emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract another 5 Gt from this balance in order to achieve a stabilization of climate warming at 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 to rule out that it will not get out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat, and the rest, i.e. 5%, is a product of light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with new bulbs with DEL, we reduce this consumption twice.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average from 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs, the kind launched this week by Philips — the company reportedly participated in a UN study — have an expected lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a red-hot bulb, giving us an idea of potential savings with a replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
All of these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they contain no mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be sorted as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless producers set up collection points.
But, as the report notes, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact light bulb, but rather thermal coal-fired power plants, which emit much of the mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these centers circulate 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
The report also details the benefits that each country would make from this international program.
Indonesia, for example, would save a billion dollars a year on electricity and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost $2.5 billion to build
