Vengeful hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double meaning.
On the one hand, an obvious scandal is revealed, a scandal that seems to be a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it speaks of profound changes at the international level, and anticipates a future dominated by regression.
But let's go in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that every document compiled by the secret service (of any nation) consists entirely of press cuts.
The "extraordinary revelations" of Americans about Berlusconi's sex life announce what everyone has been able to read for months in any newspaper (all but these two are Berlusconi's own), and the infamous caricature profile of Gaddafi has long been the subject of sketches for cabaret performers.
The rule that secret documents can only consist of known reports is fundamental to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric literature, you will see that each work repeats (about Graal, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Knights Templar or the Masons) exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to search for new information (nor does he know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who practice occultism believe only what they already know and what confirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret documents.
The informant is a lazy, and lazy (or narrow-minded) head of the secret services (and if he is not, he could be, as I know, an editor at the newspaper Libération), who considers to be true only what he admits.
The high-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy sent to the state department was the same that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why has there been so much fuss about the revelations about these documents?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person already knows, which is that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War and since heads of state can talk on the phone or fly to dinner together, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in representation, have been transformed into spy centers.
Any viewer who watches films about the investigation knows very well that it is seemingly ignored out of hypocrisy alone.
However, the fact that this is repeated publicly defames the duty of hypocrisy and casts a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can obtain the most highly classified information of the most highly classified country in the world is a severe blow, not negligible, to the prestige of this state department.
The scandal affects both the victims and its "executors".
But let's move on from here to the deep truth of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, all power could be seized, like a Big Brother controlling the every move of its people.
Orvella's prophecy has been proven since the citizen became the absolute victim of the wreath of power thanks to the ability to control every movement with the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway used, and so on.
But when we demonstrate, as it goes now, that even the "tombs" with the most secret information of the powerful cannot resist the intervention of some hacker, the control report ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power is controlled by every citizen, but every citizen, or at least a hacker - elected as the citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets be maintained?
It is true that Georg Simmel already said that a true secret is a meaningless secret (and a meaningless secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all the information about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed a mysterious, meaningless secret, because it is taken out of public life; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were meaningless secrets is to take away all power from him.
WikiLeaks made no mistake with Sarkozy or Merkel, but it did something big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this blow inflicted on such a significant power?
Obviously, in the future, states will not be able to send sensitive information online - this would be tantamount to publishing it on a poster posted on a street corner.
But it's also abundantly clear that with current technology, it's futile to hope that a message over the phone can be kept secret.
There is nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state traveled by plane and got in touch with one of his colleagues.
How can private and sensitive messages be kept secret in the future?
I am well aware that, for the moment, my forecast is science fiction and therefore fantastic, but I have to imagine government officials who travel discreetly through formalities along uncontrollable routes, carrying only the news they know by heart, or rather hiding precious information in the heel of their shoes.
The information will be preserved in unique copies in key-sealed drawers: by and large, the Watergate espionage attempt had less success than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving sideways forward, that is, backwards.
One century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet rehabilitated the telegraph based on wires (telephone).
Videocassettes (analogue) allowed cinema lovers to shoot film step by step, moving it forward and backward and revealing all the secrets of montage, whereas now CDs (digital) allow only to jump chapters, that is, macro portions.
By high-speed trains, we can travel from Rome to Milan in three hours, while we need three and a half hours for the air journey and the transport that it includes.
So it is not uncommon for politics and communication techniques to return to horse-drawn carriages.
One last note.
At other times, the press tried to understand what was being plotted in the secret of the embassy.
Now it is the embassies that are demanding confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France hacked its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to test the promises of rapidly unblocked financing (called fast start or early financing) implemented by developed countries.
And the big French hacks were exposed
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (or €420 million a year).
At the launch of COP16, the EU pulled out a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to financing fast start: a report detailing the action of its member states, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
A transparent operation priceless and valued at its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do it equally and with the same degree of precision.
The EU announces that it mobilised €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to keep its pledge of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we pay attention to detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are "new and additional" under the Copenhagen Accord to ensure that the increased burden is realised without prejudice to Public Assistance for Development.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission took 2009 as a reference: international funding was preserved, and it added 150 million for three years of the Fast Start funding title.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or public assistance for development deadlines.
France, on the other hand, considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public Aid for Development d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries may remain constant (or even decrease), in order to keep its commitment to finance "new and additional"...
Another decisive element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule there yet, and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as. France, they consider that 1€ borrowed equals 1€ donated.
Obviously, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be demonstrated for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission reduction, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present the one euro we receive as equivalent to the one euro we give... , we should not understand it in terms of our liabilities, but as the price of the loan to the creditor country (i.e. the equivalent of the interest rate).
But France can only give this justification: it is "kept" to its commitment of €420 million, of which 91.5% is a loan (€389.8 million) and 8.5% is donations (€36.1 million) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use a loan on such a scale.
Germany has claimed 46% from there, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (among others) keep their pledges with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives €1 to satisfy its promise, France gives only 10 centimes and considers this effort comparable.
Beautiful juggling stunt!
To sum up, in its financing of the "fast start", France operates with a double trick: on the one hand, with the development of the stock over time, and on the other hand, with the real financial burden.
Although it spends only €36.1 million, it manages to convince itself that it is spending €420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
Manipulation of the finance minister (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would member states continue to donate when they only need to lend?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naïve...
The early financing chapter is only a small issue, a relatively short-term one, in relation to the series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France should announce a change in its accounting arrangements for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respecting its obligations and of fairness and fairness towards the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid a debate on long-term financing deposits (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or how loans are accounted for.
France should change its attitude in order to become as progressive on these deposits as it is on others.
So everyone is pinning their hopes on the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will be coming to Cancun next week.
The surprise announcement of France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to advance the discussions.
Alarm about pesticides ingested by children.
A ten-year-old child will one day ingest 81 different chemicals, according to one study published Wednesday, from the Future Generations Association (ex-Movement for the Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which points out that its results "do not have significant statistical value due to the low number of samples analysed, but are characteristic of the issue being processed", bought between July and September food commonly consumed in four meals and one light meal as a light snack for a child of about ten years old in supermarkets in l'Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, including official recommendations — five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day — as well as confectionery, were analyzed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are carcinogenic, possible or probable, and five are clear carcinogens, as well as 37 that could interfere with internal secretion (PE) glands, according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Center for Research on Cancer.
"While in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, we can clearly see in our research that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogenic, and/or PE is striking," the association said.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone contain about ten résidui with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as is the case with about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, reported by the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for the green beans from Kenya included in the lunch, where studies have found traces of powerful insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, beefsteak from minced meat, tuna in a can, and even a bun and chewing gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyzes revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
The salmon steak for dinner was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even the analysis of a plastic plate used to heat food in a microwave oven did not escape analysis.
The ultimate risk to consumers of this 'cocktail of contaminants' is likely to be underestimated," the study concludes.
The Ecological Europe-Greens (EE-LV) association has proposed establishing a moratorium on the use of pesticides "in the face of an emergency" in order to stop the "increase in lifestyle diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the presence status of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 of which in cereals.
